<paragraph id="3D769736355CFFCBFEF7FE4C6682FDFA" blockId="48.[264,1324,283,750]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
Etymology. Akan 
<taxonomicName id="FAC9ECB5355CFFCBFDDCFE4C6547FE09" authorityName="Scarbrough Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2005" box="[531,622,444,469]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Afroestricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sankofa">
<emphasis id="0FBD4B24355CFFCBFDDCFE4C6547FE09" box="[531,622,444,469]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">sankofa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, noun in apposition, for a mythical bird that flies forward with its head turned posteriorly. The bird symbolizes the fact that the past serves as a guide for the future.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3D769736355CFFCBFEF7FDC4650CFDAA" blockId="48.[264,1324,283,750]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
Distribution (
<tableCitation id="704BA28D355CFFCBFE1BFDC46511FD92" box="[468,568,564,590]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="9.[264,343,851,872]" captionText="TABLE 1. Distribution of Afroestricus species by country." pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Tables 1</tableCitation>
, 
<tableCitation id="704BA28D355CFFCBFD89FDC4657EFD92" box="[582,599,564,590]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="10.[264,343,563,584]" captionText="TABLE 2. Phenology of Afroestricus species. Abbreviations refer to the months of the year." pageId="48" pageNumber="49">2</tableCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="A5F28BB3355CFFCBFDABFDC465E0FD92" box="[612,713,564,590]" captionStart="FIGURE 195" captionStartId="71.[264,357,1023,1044]" captionText="FIGURE 195. Distribution of three species of Afroestricus in Africa." pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 195</figureCitation>
). Known only from the 
<typeStatus id="E2722994355CFFCBFC2EFDC4633AFD92" box="[993,1043,564,590]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">type</typeStatus>
locality; collected from September to Novenber.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3D769736355CFFCBFEF7FD74659DFD32" blockId="48.[264,1324,283,750]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
Remarks. 
<taxonomicName id="FAC9ECB5355CFFCBFE7DFD74658FFD41" authorityName="Scarbrough Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2005" box="[434,678,644,669]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Afroestricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sankofa">
<emphasis id="0FBD4B24355CFFCBFE7DFD74658FFD41" box="[434,678,644,669]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Afroestricus sankofa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from congeners by the characters in the key and terminalia (
<figureCitation id="A5F28BB3355CFFCBFDF8FD5C65C3FD1A" box="[567,746,684,710]" captionStart="FIGURES 121–130" captionStartId="47.[264,370,1474,1495]" captionTargetBox="[309,1275,290,1431]" captionTargetId="figure-143@47.[292,1294,281,1476]" captionTargetPageId="47" captionText="FIGURES 121–130. Afroestricus sankofa, sp. n. Male terminalia: 121–123. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views. 124. Gonostylus. 125–126. Aedeagus, dorsal and lateral views. Female terminalia: 127–128. Dorsal and ventral views. 129. Spermatheca. 130. Genital fork." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5050655" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5050655/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Figs. 121–130</figureCitation>
). It is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="FAC9ECB5355CFFCBFBDEFD5C6352FD19" authorityName="Scarbrough Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2005" box="[1041,1147,684,709]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Afroestricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vorax">
<emphasis id="0FBD4B24355CFFCBFBDEFD5C6352FD19" box="[1041,1147,684,709]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">A. vorax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but lacks the dorsoapical notch on the epandrium.
</paragraph>
